        "d": "The cycle requires three ingredients: the closure must escape and be retained by the object, the closure must capture the object, and the capture must be strong. Remove any one and there's no cycle — which is why non-escaping closures, like the ones passed to `map` or `forEach`, never cause this; they're popped off after execution. Implicit `self` is the trap: Swift requires explicit `self.` inside escaping closures precisely to flag that you're capturing it, so the compiler nudges you to think about ownership. A common mistake is weakening `self` but then capturing another strongly-held object or a stored property reference, which keeps the cycle alive through a different edge. Note that capturing a stored property directly, like `[weak someProperty]`, captures that object, not `self`, so you must weaken the actual object that participates in the loop. When the closure is one-shot, an alternative to `[weak self]` is to nil out the stored closure inside it after it runs, severing the cycle manually.",
        "f": "Trap: A view controller stores `onTap = { print(self.title) }`. Is there a cycle if `onTap` is `nil`-ed out the first time it fires? Momentarily yes, but it's resolved once `onTap` is set to `nil`, releasing the closure and thus the strong capture of `self`."
